text.Taxonomy and naming:
Verticordia muelleriana was first formally described by Ernst Pritzel in 1904 from a specimen he collected between Watheroo and Coorow and the description was published in Botanische Jahrbücher für Systematik, Pflanzengeschichte und Pflanzengeographie. The specific epithet (muelleriana) honours Ferdinand von Mueller.There are two subspecies:

Verticordia muelleriana E.Pritzl. subsp. muelleriana which has sepals and petals 5 mm (0.20 in) long, including a fringe 1.5 mm (0.06 in)s long;
Verticordia muelleriana subsp. minor  A.S.George which has sepals 3.5 mm (0.1 in) long and petals 4 mm (0.16 in)s long, including a fringe 0.5 mm (0.02 in) long.When Alex George reviewed the genus Verticordia in 1991, he placed this species in subgenus Eperephes, section Pennuligera along with V. chrysostachys, V. lepidophylla, V. aereiflora, V. dichroma, V. x eurardyensis, V. comosa, V. argentea, V. albida, V. fragrans, V. venusta, V. forrestii, V. serotina, V. oculata, V. etheliana and V. grandis.
